,"responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-52976","V-26553","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"4921","uuid":"ed12724f-bbbd-489c-b686-c0a293902a53","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 746579D9E5ACE819D861F29165FA4EB60628F4D4\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The system must be configured to audit System - Security State Change successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226118","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226118","title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226118","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","rule_id_src":"SV-226118r852080_rule","rule_id":"SV-226118","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000109","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit System - Security System Extension successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration -> System Audit Policies -> System -> \"Audit Security System Extension\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (V-14230) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n-Open a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\n-Enter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\".\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following.  If the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem -> Security System Extension - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks.  Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised.  Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSecurity System Extension records events related to extension code being loaded by the security subsystem.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-52974","V-26555","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"3242","uuid":"1b985f4d-aa89-4658-8215-2f157dd6c44e","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8FC5E795C4442D922D48120850B91B8D74E5EB72\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The system must be configured to audit System - Security System Extension successes.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226119","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226119","title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226119","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","rule_id_src":"SV-226119r852081_rule","rule_id":"SV-226119","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000111","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit System - System Integrity successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration -> System Audit Policies -> System -> \"Audit System Integrity\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (V-14230) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n-Open a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\n-Enter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\".\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following.  If the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem -> System Integrity - Success","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks.  Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised.  Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSystem Integrity records events related to violations of integrity to the security subsystem.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-52972","V-26557","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"8529","uuid":"3dd89766-a83f-4c7a-8b9c-37bd8b01fb09","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5003E1E04A82DA7E4190340AB5A2F6429B735601\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The system must be configured to audit System - System Integrity successes.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226120","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226120","title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226120","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","rule_id_src":"SV-226120r852082_rule","rule_id":"SV-226120","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000112","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit System - System Integrity failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration -> System Audit Policies -> System -> \"Audit System Integrity\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (V-14230) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective. \n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n-Open a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\n-Enter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\".\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following.  If the system does not audit the following, this is a finding.\n\nSystem -> System Integrity - Failure","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks.  Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised.  Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nSystem Integrity records events related to violations of integrity to the security subsystem.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-52971","V-26558","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"6618","uuid":"532c858e-970a-4baf-ab46-c40573bd0e6a","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BA788B94FA7C197A3308944FB01CA2A7C60B695F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The system must be configured to audit System - System Integrity failures.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226121","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226121","title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226121","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","rule_id_src":"SV-226121r794316_rule","rule_id":"SV-226121","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000200","rule_title":"Audit data must be reviewed on a regular basis.","fix_text":"Review audit logs on a predetermined scheduled.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine whether audit logs are reviewed on a predetermined schedule.  If audit logs are not reviewed on a regular basis, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To be of value, audit logs from critical systems must be reviewed on a regular basis.  Critical systems should be reviewed on a daily basis to identify security breaches and potential weaknesses in the security structure.  This can be done with the use of monitoring software or other utilities for this purpose.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51561","V-36670","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3897","uuid":"84dc6650-a5e2-46e2-b627-3d9e3624f5e3","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-226122","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226122","title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226122","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","rule_id_src":"SV-226122r794317_rule","rule_id":"SV-226122","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000201","rule_title":"Audit data must be retained for at least one year.","fix_text":"Ensure the audit data is retained for at least a year.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine whether audit data is retained for at least one year.  If the audit data is not retained for at least a year, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Audit records are essential for investigating system activity after the fact.  Retention periods for audit data are determined based on the sensitivity of the data handled by the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51563","V-36671","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8030","uuid":"2f669de8-9127-4a91-8b78-bff14fc872e4","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 038D113C2767B7EEEAE296A0D95035D2AE5F2898\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Audit data must be retained for at least one year.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226123","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226123","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226123","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-226123r877390_rule","rule_id":"SV-226123","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000203-01","rule_title":"Audit records must be backed up onto a different system or media than the system being audited.","fix_text":"Establish and implement a process for backing up log data to another system or media other than the system being audited.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if a process to back up log data to a different system or media than the system being audited has been implemented.  If it has not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protection of log data includes assuring the log data is not accidentally lost or deleted.  Audit information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51566","V-36672","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"6605","uuid":"c6d163d5-8b2f-4fdb-be47-c4013a14624e","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 144FC05A414ECA8C55BAF6656D54755D390CDC0E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Audit records must be backed up onto a different system or media than the system being audited.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226124","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226124","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226124","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-226124r877390_rule","rule_id":"SV-226124","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000203-02","rule_title":"The operating system must, at a minimum, off-load audit records of interconnected systems in real time and off-load standalone systems weekly.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to, at a minimum, off-load audit records of interconnected systems in real time and off-load standalone systems weekly.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system, at a minimum, off-loads audit records of interconnected systems in real time and off-loads standalone systems weekly.  If it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protection of log data includes assuring the log data is not accidentally lost or deleted.  Audit information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-72133","V-57719","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"5378","uuid":"920e61d0-6311-42a8-a5a7-6016e1a1f16b","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5E029EFEDCF6FF370A297CDB9E48B842ED25659C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The operating system must, at a minimum, off-load audit records of interconnected systems in real time and off-load standalone systems weekly.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226125","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226125","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226125","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-226125r794760_rule","rule_id":"SV-226125","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000204","rule_title":"Permissions for the Application event log must prevent access by nonprivileged accounts.","fix_text":"Ensure the permissions on the Application event log (Application.evtx) are configured to prevent standard user accounts or groups from having greater than Read access.  The default permissions listed below satisfy this requirement:\n\nEventlog - Full Control\nSYSTEM - Full Control\nAdministrators - Full Control\n\nThe default location is the \"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\\WINEVT\\LOGS\" directory.\n\nIf the location of the logs has been changed, when adding Eventlog to the permissions, it must be entered as \"NT Service\\Eventlog\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the permissions on the Application event log (Application.evtx).  Standard user accounts or groups must not have greater than Read access.  The default permissions listed below satisfy this requirement:\n\nEventlog - Full Control\nSYSTEM - Full Control\nAdministrators - Full Control\n\nThe default location is the \"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\\WINEVT\\LOGS\" directory.  They may have been moved to another folder.\n\nIf the permissions for these files are not as restrictive as the ACLs listed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks.  Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised.  The Application event log may be  susceptible to tampering if proper permissions are not applied.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51569","V-36722","CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164"],"reference_identifier":"7044","uuid":"776718b6-d512-4bf9-820c-feeee9554f4b","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EC7F7D17D5EECF50885E4B965F52AD0774A1B5F0\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Permissions for the Application event log must prevent access by nonprivileged accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226126","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226126","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226126","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-226126r794762_rule","rule_id":"SV-226126","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000205","rule_title":"Permissions for the Security event log must prevent access by nonprivileged accounts.","fix_text":"Ensure the permissions on the Security event log (Security.evtx) are configured to prevent standard user accounts or groups from having access.  The default permissions listed below satisfy this requirement:\n\nEventlog - Full Control\nSYSTEM - Full Control\nAdministrators - Full Control\n\nThe default location is the \"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\\WINEVT\\LOGS\" directory.\n\nIf the location of the logs has been changed, when adding Eventlog to the permissions, it must be entered as \"NT Service\\Eventlog\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the permissions on the Security event log (Security.evtx).  Standard user accounts or groups must not have access.  The default permissions listed below satisfy this requirement:\n\nEventlog - Full Control\nSYSTEM - Full Control\nAdministrators - Full Control\n\nThe default location is the \"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\\WINEVT\\LOGS\" directory.  They may have been moved to another folder.\n\nIf the permissions for these files are not as restrictive as the ACLs listed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks.  Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised.  The Security event log may disclose sensitive information or be  susceptible to tampering if proper permissions are not applied.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-36723","SV-51571","CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164"],"reference_identifier":"8282","uuid":"1eba5705-ccbd-45de-871d-898a49efabd7","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DA79D841C3BA4D28D46157CACD54E00B9700865C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Permissions for the Security event log must prevent access by nonprivileged accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226127","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226127","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226127","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-226127r794764_rule","rule_id":"SV-226127","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000206","rule_title":"Permissions for the System event log must prevent access by nonprivileged accounts.","fix_text":"Ensure the permissions on the System event log (System.evtx) are configured to prevent standard user accounts or groups from having greater than Read access.  The default permissions listed below satisfy this requirement:\n\nEventlog - Full Control\nSYSTEM - Full Control\nAdministrators - Full Control\n\nThe default location is the \"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\\WINEVT\\LOGS\" directory.\n\nIf the location of the logs has been changed, when adding Eventlog to the permissions, it must be entered as \"NT Service\\Eventlog\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the permissions on the System event log (System.evtx).  Standard user accounts or groups must not have greater than Read access.  The default permissions listed below satisfy this requirement:\n\nEventlog - Full Control\nSYSTEM - Full Control\nAdministrators - Full Control\n\nThe default location is the \"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\\WINEVT\\LOGS\" directory.  They may have been moved to another folder.\n\nIf the permissions for these files are not as restrictive as the ACLs listed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks.  Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised.  The System event log may be  susceptible to tampering if proper permissions are not applied.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-36724","SV-51572","CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164"],"reference_identifier":"3635","uuid":"e4d53897-924b-4b44-b323-cdff9ec4d35e","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DFF00003F8545BEE0E6BE36EFD0FB6CD52B9D954\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Permissions for the System event log must prevent access by nonprivileged accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226128","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226128","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226128","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-226128r852085_rule","rule_id":"SV-226128","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000207-DC","rule_title":"Active Directory Group Policy objects must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for Group Policy objects to include the following.\n\nThis can be done at the Policy level in Active Directory to apply to all group policies.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\" (available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\").\n\nSelect \"Advanced Features\" from the \"View\" Menu.\n\nNavigate to [Domain] >> System >> Policies in the left panel.\n\nRight click \"Policies\", select \"Properties\".\n\nSelect the \"Security\" tab.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button.\n\nSelect the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects or Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nThe three Success types listed below are defaults inherited from the Parent Object. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special (Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions; Properties: all \"Write\" type selected)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - blank (Permissions: none selected; Properties: one instance - Write gPLink, one instance - Write gPOptions)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant Organization Unit Objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the auditing configuration for all Group Policy objects.\n\nOpen \"Group Policy Management\". (Available from various menus, or run \"gpmc.msc\".)\n\nNavigate to \"Group Policy Objects\" in the domain being reviewed (Forest >> Domains >> Domain). \n\nFor each Group Policy object: \n\nSelect the Group Policy Object item in the left pane.\n\nSelect the \"Delegation\" tab in the right pane.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button.\n\nSelect the \"Advanced\" button again and then the \"Auditing\" tab.\n\nIf the audit settings for any Group Policy object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects or Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nThe three Success types listed below are defaults inherited from the Parent Object. Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special (Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions; Properties: all \"Write\" type selected)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant groupPolicyContainer objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - blank (Permissions: none selected; Properties: one instance - Write gPLink, one instance - Write gPOptions)\nInherited from - Parent Object\nApplies to - Descendant Organization Unit Objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data.  The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object.  A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential.  This includes Group Policy objects.  Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain.  The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51169","V-39325","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"9148","uuid":"d1fa54e3-f4a1-48bd-a87e-7590ad77eecc","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9BB019504A9A87DBE11952B1FBEE54A6F371BB5E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Active Directory Group Policy objects must be configured with proper audit settings.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226129","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226129","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226129","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-226129r852086_rule","rule_id":"SV-226129","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000208-DC","rule_title":"The Active Directory Domain object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for Domain object to include the following.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - Special\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Domain Users\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Administrators\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner.)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the auditing configuration for the Domain object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\".  (Available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\".)\nEnsure Advanced Features is selected in the View menu.\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\nRight click the domain name and select Properties.\nSelect the Security tab.\nSelect the Advanced button and then the Auditing tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Domain object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - Special\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Domain Users\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Administrators\nAccess - All extended rights\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data.  The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object.  A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential.  This includes the Domain object.  Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain.  The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51170","V-39326","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"1944","uuid":"b1209381-4e62-4173-91cd-2a689bf5f8a2","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 05C968F44CBF697E9EB404A472502812B3FB5E2C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Active Directory Domain object must be configured with proper audit settings.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226130","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226130","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226130","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-226130r852087_rule","rule_id":"SV-226130","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000209-DC","rule_title":"The Active Directory Infrastructure object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for Infrastructure object to include the following.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, All extended rights, Change infrastructure master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the auditing configuration for Infrastructure object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\".  (Available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\".)\nEnsure Advanced Features is selected in the View menu.\nSelect the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\nRight click the Infrastructure object in the right pane and select Properties.\nSelect the Security tab.\nSelect the Advanced button and then the Auditing tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Infrastructure object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n(Access - Special = Permissions: Write all properties, All extended rights, Change infrastructure master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data.  The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object.  A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential.  This includes the Infrastructure object.  Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain.  The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51171","V-39327","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"1584","uuid":"1e720cd0-a25d-403c-84d3-f7dc557973f5","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 47339FD8FE5B82060FC1F075F731273F72BF3797\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Active Directory Infrastructure object must be configured with proper audit settings.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226131","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226131","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226131","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-226131r852088_rule","rule_id":"SV-226131","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000210-DC","rule_title":"The Active Directory Domain Controllers Organizational Unit (OU) object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for Domain Controllers OU object to include the following.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: all create, delete and modify permissions)\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Write all properties\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the auditing configuration for the Domain Controller OU object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\".  (Available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\".)\nEnsure Advanced Features is selected in the View menu.\nSelect the Domain Controllers OU under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\nRight click the Domain Controllers OU object and select Properties.\nSelect the Security tab.\nSelect the Advanced button and then the Auditing tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the Domain Controllers OU object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Permissions: all create, delete and modify permissions)\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Write all properties\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object and all descendant objects\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data.  The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object.  A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential.  This includes the Domain Controller OU object.  Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain.  The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisifes: SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51172","V-39328","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"1684","uuid":"e0241016-af3e-48c0-9140-5257f3f98357","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0ACFCF495B62DB72D41F229ADC169F5A7DBAD687\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Active Directory Domain Controllers Organizational Unit (OU) object must be configured with proper audit settings.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226132","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226132","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226132","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-226132r852089_rule","rule_id":"SV-226132","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000211-DC","rule_title":"The Active Directory AdminSDHolder object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for AdminSDHolder object to include the following.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the auditing configuration for the AdminSDHolder object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\".  (Available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\".)\nEnsure Advanced Features is selected in the View menu.\nSelect System under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\nRight click the AdminSDHolder object in the right pane and select Properties.\nSelect the Security tab.\nSelect the Advanced button and then the Auditing tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the AdminSDHolder object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\nApplies to - This object only\n(Access - Special = Write all properties, Modify permissions, Modify owner)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)\nApplies to - Descendant Organizational Unit objects","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data.  The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object.  A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential.  This includes the AdminSDHolder object.  Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain.  The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51173","V-39329","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"5314","uuid":"12d4f757-23e2-4890-8995-fa2d73240eb8","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AAD7E2E19B28BAE726E529376C7115C59BC557FD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Active Directory AdminSDHolder object must be configured with proper audit settings.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226133","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226133","title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226133","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","rule_id_src":"SV-226133r852090_rule","rule_id":"SV-226133","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000212-DC","rule_title":"The Active Directory RID Manager$ object must be configured with proper audit settings.","fix_text":"Configure the audit settings for RID Manager$ object to include the following.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n (Access - Special = Write all properties, All extended rights, Change RID master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the auditing configuration for the RID Manager$ object.\n\nOpen \"Active Directory Users and Computers\".  (Available from various menus or run \"dsa.msc\".)\nEnsure Advanced Features is selected in the View menu.\nSelect System under the domain being reviewed in the left pane.\nRight-click the RID Manager$ object in the right pane and select Properties.\nSelect the Security tab.\nSelect the Advanced button and then the Auditing tab.\n\nIf the audit settings on the RID Manager$ object are not at least as inclusive as those below, this is a finding.\n\nType - Fail\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Full Control\nInherited from - None\n\nThe success types listed below are defaults.  Where Special is listed in the summary screens for Access, detailed Permissions are provided for reference, various Properties selections may also exist by default.\n\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - Special\nInherited from - None\n (Access - Special = Write all properties, All extended rights, Change RID master)\n\nTwo instances with the following summary information will be listed.\nType - Success\nPrincipal - Everyone\nAccess - (blank)\nInherited from - (CN of domain)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When inappropriate audit settings are configured for directory service database objects, it may be possible for a user or process to update the data without generating any tracking data.  The impact of missing audit data is related to the type of object.  A failure to capture audit data for objects used by identification, authentication, or authorization functions could degrade or eliminate the ability to track changes to access policy for systems or data. \n\nFor Active Directory (AD), there are a number of critical object types in the domain naming context of the AD database for which auditing is essential.  This includes the RID Manager$ object.  Because changes to these objects can significantly impact access controls or the availability of systems, the absence of auditing data makes it impossible to identify the source of changes that impact the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems throughout an AD domain.  The lack of proper auditing can result in insufficient forensic evidence needed to investigate an incident and prosecute the intruder.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51174","V-39330","CCI-000172","CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"5624","uuid":"6f5559e3-55d0-4138-811d-6580fc4d1d9e","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-226134","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226134","title":"SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226134","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098","rule_id_src":"SV-226134r794458_rule","rule_id":"SV-226134","rule_version":"WN12-AU-000213","rule_title":"Event Viewer must be protected from unauthorized modification and deletion.","fix_text":"Ensure only TrustedInstaller has permissions to change or modify Event Viewer (\"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\\Eventvwr.exe).\n\nThe default permissions below satisfy this requirement.\nTrustedInstaller - Full Control\nAdministrators, SYSTEM, Users, ALL APPLICATION PACKAGES - Read & Execute","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the permissions on Event Viewer only allow TrustedInstaller permissions to change or modify.  If any groups or accounts other than TrustedInstaller have Full control or Modify, this is a finding.\n\nNavigate to \"%SystemRoot%\\SYSTEM32\".\nView the permissions on \"Eventvwr.exe\".\n\nThe default permissions below satisfy this requirement.\nTrustedInstaller - Full Control\nAdministrators, SYSTEM, Users, ALL APPLICATION PACKAGES - Read & Execute","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nOperating systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools and the corresponding rights the user enjoys in order to make access decisions regarding the modification or deletion of audit tools.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-72135","V-57721","CCI-001494","CCI-001495"],"reference_identifier":"9673","uuid":"a6357271-24ba-4d28-9596-ffd72e67121d","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-226135","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226135","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226135","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","rule_id_src":"SV-226135r794411_rule","rule_id":"SV-226135","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000001","rule_title":"The Mapper I/O network protocol (LLTDIO) driver must be disabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> Link-Layer Topology Discovery -> \"Turn on Mapper I/O (LLTDIO) driver\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry values do not exist or are not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\LLTD\\\n\nValue Name: AllowLLTDIOOndomain\nValue Name: AllowLLTDIOOnPublicNet\nValue Name: EnableLLTDIO\nValue Name: ProhibitLLTDIOOnPrivateNet\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The Mapper I/O network protocol (LLTDIO) driver allows the discovery of the connected network and allows various options to be enabled.  Disabling this helps protect the system from potentially discovering and connecting to unauthorized devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-15696","SV-53072","CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"5686","uuid":"56cb0c11-b6e8-49c0-9cef-dcd996a31338","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E5797E3B2E19E13F6955E7EAD21D008C2FDCFF7D\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Mapper I/O network protocol (LLTDIO) driver must be disabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226136","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226136","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226136","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","rule_id_src":"SV-226136r794412_rule","rule_id":"SV-226136","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000002","rule_title":"The Responder network protocol driver must be disabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> Link-Layer Topology Discovery -> \"Turn on Responder (RSPNDR) driver\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry values do not exist or are not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\LLTD\\\n\nValue Name: AllowRspndrOndomain\nValue Name: AllowRspndrOnPublicNet\nValue Name: EnableRspndr\nValue Name: ProhibitRspndrOnPrivateNet\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The Responder network protocol driver allows a computer to be discovered and located on a network.  Disabling this helps protect the system from potentially being discovered and connected to by unauthorized devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-15697","SV-53081","CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"3828","uuid":"30253ddc-89f9-4fdf-8d62-e4e467608daa","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B40F18893F27FDA7795976F754043DCA4FF1189\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Responder network protocol driver must be disabled.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226137","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226137","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226137","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","rule_id_src":"SV-226137r794413_rule","rule_id":"SV-226137","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000003","rule_title":"Windows Peer-to-Peer networking services must be turned off.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> Microsoft Peer-to-Peer Networking Services -> \"Turn off Microsoft Peer-to-Peer Networking Services\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Peernet\\\n\nValue Name: Disabled\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 1","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Peer-to-Peer applications can allow unauthorized access to a system and exposure of sensitive data.  This setting will turn off the Microsoft Peer-to-Peer Networking Service.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-15666","SV-53012","CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"7350","uuid":"185c81cd-bda1-4a23-9e04-55fc03107b68","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9FD044295ABB191B3B587BCAB1D8B090FD6AFF27\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Windows Peer-to-Peer networking services must be turned off.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226138","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226138","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226138","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","rule_id_src":"SV-226138r794414_rule","rule_id":"SV-226138","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000004","rule_title":"Network Bridges must be prohibited in Windows.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> Network Connections -> \"Prohibit installation and configuration of Network Bridge on your DNS domain network\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Network Connections\\\n\nValue Name: NC_AllowNetBridge_NLA\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A Network Bridge can connect two or more network segments, allowing unauthorized access or exposure of sensitive data.  This setting prevents a Network Bridge from being installed and configured.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-15667","SV-53014","CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"6057","uuid":"3de2d49b-7227-4237-a0c5-90cab802bc92","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 02A7E2B8DF75826545FE5141073BE768746ACDC8\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'Network Bridges must be prohibited in Windows.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226139","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226139","title":"SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226139","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068","rule_id_src":"SV-226139r794452_rule","rule_id":"SV-226139","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000005","rule_title":"Domain users must be required to elevate when setting a networks location.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> Network Connections -> \"Require domain users to elevate when setting a network's location\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Network Connections\\\n\nValue Name: NC_StdDomainUserSetLocation\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 1","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Selecting an incorrect network location may allow greater exposure of a system.  Elevation is required by default on nondomain systems to change network location.  This setting configures elevation to also be required on domain-joined systems.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-21960","SV-53182","CCI-001084"],"reference_identifier":"7283","uuid":"1fde7021-3a1b-453b-888c-8b8e09caba30","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 848E8B284DC7149DDBAE80051784CD8AE83DFF87\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Domain users must be required to elevate when setting a networks location.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226140","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226140","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226140","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-226140r794494_rule","rule_id":"SV-226140","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000006","rule_title":"All Direct Access traffic must be routed through the internal network.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> Network Connections -> \"Route all traffic through the internal network\" to \"Enabled: Enabled State\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\TCPIP\\v6Transition\\\n\nValue Name: Force_Tunneling\n\nType: REG_SZ\nValue: Enabled","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Routing all Direct Access  traffic through the internal network allows monitoring and prevents split tunneling.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-53183","V-21961","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2569","uuid":"42169066-46a1-4fa8-9943-f3ca728fad29","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3D6C88C4D18AF4DF885A48A0261690DFB2B89D91\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'All Direct Access traffic must be routed through the internal network.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226145","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226145","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226145","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-226145r794495_rule","rule_id":"SV-226145","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000011","rule_title":"IP stateless autoconfiguration limits state must be enabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> TCPIP Settings -> Parameters -> \"Set IP Stateless Autoconfiguration Limits State\" to \"Enabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry value does not exist or is not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\System\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\Tcpip\\Parameters\\\n\nValue Name: EnableIPAutoConfigurationLimits\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 1","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"IP stateless autoconfiguration could configure routes that circumvent preferred routes if not limited.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-51605","V-36673","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5157","uuid":"62ada0be-752b-41e3-90fe-b38a60829104","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 438E37832F19ADD1AD29F7CDA7FFB06DF0EC3153\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'IP stateless autoconfiguration limits state must be enabled.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226146","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226146","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-226146","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","rule_id_src":"SV-226146r794417_rule","rule_id":"SV-226146","rule_version":"WN12-CC-000012","rule_title":"The configuration of wireless devices using Windows Connect Now must be disabled.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> Windows Connect Now -> \"Configuration of wireless settings using Windows Connect Now\" to \"Disabled\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following registry values do not exist or are not configured as specified, this is a finding:\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\WCN\\Registrars\\\n\nValue Name: DisableFlashConfigRegistrar\nValue Name: DisableInBand802DOT11Registrar\nValue Name: DisableUPnPRegistrar\nValue Name: DisableWPDRegistrar\nValue Name: EnableRegistrars\n\nType: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_Server_2012-2012_R2_DC_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Windows Connect Now allows the discovery and configuration of devices over wireless.  Wireless devices must be managed.  If a rogue device is connected to a system, there is potential for sensitive information to be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-15698","SV-53085","CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"7007","uuid":"556c2dac-7f1f-4603-8e78-79b73f1b2ea6","stig_uuid":"3c28ef40-d2e7-4de8-80c7-a2d09a1263eb","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsServer2012R2DC_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E83D928C239F66D58865B40AD0E5CD1D6432AD75\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The configuration of wireless devices using Windows Connect Now must be disabled.' matches the expected value on the Windows Server 2012 R2 domain controller."},{"group_id_src":"V-226147","group_tree":[{"id":"V-226147","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group